definition.value: An EC 2.1.1.* (methyltransferases) inhibitor that interferes with the action of site-specific DNA-methyltransferase (adenine-specific), EC 2.1.1.72.
An organic cation obtained by protonation of the four free amino groups of neamine; major species at pH 7.3.
An organic cation obtained by protonation of the six free amino groups of neomycin C; major species at pH 7.3.
An organophosphate oxoanion arising from deprotonation of two of the the three diphosphate OH groups of guanosine 5'-diphosphate.
A carbohydrate derivative that is any derivative of a polysaccharide.
Substances which are added to food in order to prevent decomposition caused by  microbial growth or by undesirable chemical changes.

A food preservative which prevents decomposition of food by preventing the growth of fungi or bacteria. In European countries, E-numbers for permitted food preservatives are from E200 to E299, divided into sorbates (E200-209), benzoates (E210-219), sulfites (E220-229), phenols and formates (E230-239), nitrates (E240-259), acetates (E260-269), lactates (E270-279), propionates (E280-289) and others (E290-299).
A compound that inhibits the action of gamma-aminobutyric acid.
Any substance which is used to neutralise stomach acidity.
An ammonium ion derivative resulting from the protonation of the nitrogen atom of a primary amino compound. Major species at pH 7.3.
An unsaturated fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of 5-hydroxy-6E,8Z,11Z,14Z-icosatetraenoic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group.
A long-chain fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of 5-oxo-ETE, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group.
A 2-hydroxydicarboxylic acid that is succinic acid in which one of the hydrogens attached to a carbon is replaced by a hydroxy group.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the acyl groups at C-1 and C-2 contain 32 carbons in total with 1 double bond.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the acyl groups at C-1 and C-2 contain 32 carbons in total with 0 double bonds.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the acyl groups at C-1 and C-2 contain 34 carbons in total with 0 double bonds.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the acyl groups at C-1 and C-2 contain 36 carbons in total with 1 double bond.
Any dicarboxylic acid that contains four carbon atoms.
An N-acyl-L-alpha-amino acid anion that is the conjugate base of carnosine, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group.
An amino acid zwitterion arising from transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group of any N-alkylglycine; major species at pH 7.3.
An amino acid zwitterion arising from transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group of alanine; major species at pH 7.3.
An alpha-amino acid anion that is the conjugate base of citrulline, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group.
A monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of creatine, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group.
Any glycine derivative in which glycine is substituted at position 2 by an alkyl group.
An alpha-amino acid anion that is the conjugate base of homocysteine, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group.
Any compound that is able to protect normal cells from the damage caused by radiation therapy.
A L-alpha-amino acid anion obtained by deprotonation of S-adenosyl-L-homocysteine.
An N-acyl-L-alpha-amino acid anion obtained by deprotonation of any folic acid.
Any branched-chain fatty acid anion containing methyl branches only.
A folate obtained by deprotonation of any tetrahydrofolic acid.
A sulfonium betaine that is a conjugate base of S-adenosyl-L-methionine obtained by the deprotonation of the carboxy group.
Any compound that has anti-inflammatory effects.
A molecule that can substitute for a normal nucleobase in nucleic acids.
Any 1,4-benzoquinone carrying a single hydroxy substituent.

A zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the phosphate to the amino group of any lysophosphatidylethanolamine. The structure is depicted in the image where R(1) = acyl, R(2) = H or where R(1) = H, R(2) = acyl.
A dicarboxylic acid anion arising from deprotonation of both carboxylic acid functions of 5,6,7,8-tetrahydrofolic acid; major structure at pH 7.3
Any monocyclic heteroarene consisting of a five-membered ring containing nitrogen. Azoles can also contain one or more other non-carbon atoms, such as nitrogen, sulfur or oxygen.

A glycerophosphocholine that is sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which positions 1 and 2 are substituted by unspecified acyl and alkyl groups, and in which the positions of the acyl and alkyl groups are also unspecified.
Any substance that induces the process of apoptosis (programmed cell death) in multi-celled organisms.
An anionic phospholipid obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH group of any lysophosphatidyl-1D-myo-inositol; major species at pH 7.3.
A nucleotide-sugar oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the phospho and carboxy groups of any CMP-N-acyl-beta-neuraminic acid; major species at pH 7.3.
A hormone agonist that binds to and activates progesterone receptors.
An enzyme inhibitor that inhibits the action of a transferase (EC 2.*)
An organic cation that is the conjugate acid of (R)-adrenaline, obtained by protonation of the amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
An icosatetraenoic acid having four cis double bonds at positions 8, 11, 14 and 17.
An unsaturated fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of all-cis-8,11,14,17-icosatetraenoic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group.
Benzoquinones with at least one hydroxy substituent.
An amino-acid anion in which the amino group is situated gamma- to the carboxylate group.
A carbohydrate acid anion obtained by deprotonation of any aldonic acid. Major structure at pH 7.3 of aldonate compounds.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine zwitterion in which the acyl groups at C-1 and C-2 contain 32 carbons in total with 0 double bonds.
